Note: ============================================================================
Note: ERLANG TO HIR TRANSLATOR - Production Translation Frontend
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Translates Erlang AST to HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation)
Note: Handles: actor model, message passing, pattern matching, guards,
Note: concurrent functional programming, fault tolerance
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIRNodes

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TRANSLATION CONTEXT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Translation context bundles every piece of mutable state the Erlang
translator needs: the current module name, its exported function set,
record/type indexes for resolution, a local-variable type environment,
an accumulating error list, and a counter for synthetic temp names.
Bundling avoids threading many parameters through every translate_*
call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Field-based struct. current_module is the module being translated.
exported_functions is a list of {name, arity} pairs read from the
`-export(...)` attribute. records/types/local_vars are dictionaries
populated as declarations are encountered. errors collects diagnostic
strings without aborting translation. next_temp_id is a monotonic
counter used by generate_temp_var.
@End Implementation

Type called "ErlangTranslationContext":
    current_module as String
    exported_functions as List[Dictionary[String, Integer]]  Note: {name, arity}
    records as Dictionary[String, ErlangRecord]
    types as Dictionary[String, ErlangTypeDecl]
    local_vars as Dictionary[String, HIRType]
    errors as List[String]
    next_temp_id as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructs an empty context bound to the supplied module name. All
collections start empty; populating them is the responsibility of
translate_erlang_module_to_hir as it walks the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds the ErlangTranslationContext struct; sets current_module from
the parameter; initialises exported_functions/errors as empty lists,
records/types/local_vars as empty dictionaries, and next_temp_id to 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_translation_context" that takes module_name as String returns ErlangTranslationContext:
    Let ctx be a value of type ErlangTranslationContext
    Set ctx.current_module to module_name
    Set ctx.exported_functions to proc list_create from ListCore
    Set ctx.records to proc dict_create from DictCore
    Set ctx.types to proc dict_create from DictCore
    Set ctx.local_vars to proc dict_create from DictCore
    Set ctx.errors to proc list_create from ListCore
    Set ctx.next_temp_id to 0
    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Generates fresh synthetic variable names for cases where the
translator needs to bind a value (e.g. for desugaring pattern matches
into explicit dispatch). Names use a `$erlang_temp_` prefix so they
cannot collide with Erlang identifiers (which don't allow `$`).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Concatenates "$erlang_temp_" with the string form of next_temp_id,
then increments next_temp_id so the next call produces a fresh name.
Returns the new name.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_temp_var" that takes ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns String:
    Let temp_name be "$erlang_temp_" joined with string representation of ctx.next_temp_id
    Set ctx.next_temp_id to ctx.next_temp_id plus 1
    Return temp_name
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Module translation walks attributes first to extract the exported-functions
list (the only attribute with HIR-level effect; others are pre-processor or
documentation), then indexes records and types into name-keyed maps so later
expression translation can resolve record/type references in constant time.
Function translation is the final pass because functions may refer to
records and types declared anywhere in the module, even after the function
itself - Erlang's parser collects declarations across the whole module
before semantic processing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_erlang_module_to_hir" that takes erl_module as ErlangModule returns HIRModule:
    Let ctx be create_translation_context with erl_module.module_name

    Note: Process module attributes to extract exports and metadata
    For Each attr as ErlangAttribute in erl_module.attributes:
        If attr.attr_type is equal to "export" and length of attr.attr_values is greater than 0:
            Let export_list be attr.attr_values at index 0
            Set ctx.exported_functions to export_list
        End If
    End For

    Note: Index records by name
    For Each record as ErlangRecord in erl_module.records:
        Set ctx.records at key record.name to record
    End For

    Note: Index types by name
    For Each type_decl as ErlangTypeDecl in erl_module.types:
        Set ctx.types at key type_decl.name to type_decl
    End For

    Note: Translate all functions
    Let hir_functions be a list containing nothing

    For Each erl_func as ErlangFunction in erl_module.functions:
        Let hir_func be translate_function with erl_func, ctx
        Add hir_func to end of hir_functions
    End For

    Note: Create HIR module
    Let hir_module be a value of type HIRModule with
        name as erl_module.module_name,
        functions as hir_functions,
        types as a list containing nothing,
        imports as a list containing nothing,
        exports as ctx.exported_functions

    Return hir_module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Erlang functions are syntactically a sequence of clauses sharing a name+arity,
each with its own pattern list and optional guard sequence. HIR has no native
multi-clause construct, so we collapse to a single function whose body is a
pattern-matching dispatch. We special-case the common single-clause-no-guards
shape with a direct body translation to avoid wrapping trivial functions in
an unconditional if-statement that the optimiser would have to undo. The
exported flag is set by walking ctx.exported_functions and matching on
name+arity, the same identity Erlang uses for export resolution.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function" that takes erl_func as ErlangFunction, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRFunction:
    Note: Erlang functions can have multiple clauses with different patterns
    Note: Translate to single HIR function with pattern matching dispatch

    Let func_name be erl_func.name
    Let arity be erl_func.arity

    Note: Create parameter list from arity
    Let parameters be a list containing nothing
    Let param_types be a list containing nothing

    For i from 0 to arity minus 1:
        Let param_name be "arg" joined with string representation of i
        Add param_name to end of parameters

        Note: Erlang is dynamically typed - use Any type
        Let param_type be create_hir_type with "any" and a list containing nothing
        Add param_type to end of param_types
    End For

    Note: Create function signature
    Let return_type be create_hir_type with "any" and a list containing nothing

    Note: Build function body
    Let body be a list containing nothing

    Note: If single clause without guards or patterns, translate directly
    If length of erl_func.clauses is equal to 1:
        Let clause be erl_func.clauses at index 0 of type ErlangFunctionClause

        Let has_complex_patterns be false
        For Each pattern as ErlangExpression in clause.patterns:
            If not is_simple_variable_pattern with pattern:
                Set has_complex_patterns to true
                Break
            End If
        End For

        If not has_complex_patterns and length of clause.guards is equal to 0:
            Note: Simple case - just translate body
            Set body to translate_expressions with clause.body and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Note: Complex patterns or guards - build match dispatch
            Set body to translate_clauses_with_dispatch with erl_func.clauses, parameters, ctx
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Note: Multiple clauses - build match dispatch
        Set body to translate_clauses_with_dispatch with erl_func.clauses, parameters, ctx
    End If

    Note: Check if function is exported
    Let is_exported be false
    For Each export_info in ctx.exported_functions:
        If export_info at key "name" is equal to func_name and export_info at key "arity" is equal to arity:
            Set is_exported to true
            Break
        End If
    End For

    Let hir_func be a value of type HIRFunction with
        name as func_name,
        parameters as parameters,
        param_types as param_types,
        return_type as return_type,
        body as body,
        is_public as is_exported

    Return hir_func
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifies patterns that bind a name (or the wildcard) without performing any
structural destructuring. The result drives translate_function's fast path:
single-clause functions whose patterns are ALL simple variables can skip the
match-dispatch machinery entirely. Underscore is treated as simple even
though it is technically an atom because it never fails to match and
contributes no bindings.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_simple_variable_pattern" that takes pattern as ErlangExpression returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if pattern is just a simple variable (no destructuring)
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Return true
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "atom" and pattern.expr_data at key "value" is equal to "_":
        Return true  Note: Underscore wildcard
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-clause functions become an if-chain where each clause becomes one
if-statement. We walk clauses in source order because Erlang's first-match
semantics requires the first matching clause to win - converting to nested
else-if would also work but the flat sequence is easier for downstream
optimisers to flatten or convert into a switch. Every dispatch chain
terminates with an erlang:error(function_clause) call so the runtime
behaviour mirrors what the Erlang VM produces when no clause matches.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_clauses_with_dispatch" that takes clauses as List[ErlangFunctionClause], parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns List[HIRStatement]:
    Note: Build pattern matching dispatch for multiple clauses
    Let body be a list containing nothing

    Note: Generate nested if-else chain or match statement for clauses
    For i from 0 to length of clauses minus 1:
        Let clause be clauses at index i

        Note: Build condition for this clause (pattern matching + guards)
        Let clause_condition be build_clause_condition with clause, parameters, ctx

        Note: Translate clause body
        Let clause_body be translate_expressions with clause.body and ctx

        Note: Create conditional block
        If i is equal to 0:
            Note: First clause - create if statement
            Let if_stmt be create_hir_if with clause_condition, clause_body, a list containing nothing
            Add if_stmt to end of body
        Otherwise:
            Note: Subsequent clauses - add else-if. When the clause has multiple
            Note: guards, fold them into a nested if-chain with build_guard_chain
            Note: before emitting the conditional block. clause.guards is the
            Note: list of guard sequences; we pass it directly along with the
            Note: translated clause body which build_guard_chain wraps.
            Let guard_count be proc list_length from List with clause.guards
            Let final_body be clause_body
            If guard_count is greater than 1:
                Set final_body to proc build_guard_chain with ctx, clause.guards, clause_body
            End If
            Set if_stmt to create_hir_if with clause_condition, final_body, a list containing nothing
            Add if_stmt to end of body
        End If
    End For

    Note: Add function_clause error if no clause matches
    Let function_clause_atom be create_hir_atom with "function_clause"
    Let function_clause_args be a list containing function_clause_atom
    Let error_call be create_hir_call with "erlang:error", function_clause_args
    Add error_call to end of body

    Return body
End Process

@Reasoning:
A clause matches when ALL its patterns match the corresponding parameters AND
all its guards succeed. We linearise that into a list of boolean expressions
(one per pattern check, one per guard expression) and AND them all together.
The AND chain is left-associative because Erlang guards short-circuit
left-to-right and our build_pattern_match emits checks that can fail safely
in any order. When no conditions exist (degenerate empty pattern list), we
return literal true so the if-statement degenerates to an unconditional
branch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "build_clause_condition" that takes clause as ErlangFunctionClause, parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note: Build condition expression that checks if parameters match patterns and guards

    Let conditions be a list containing nothing

    Note: Build pattern matching conditions
    For i from 0 to length of clause.patterns minus 1:
        Let pattern be clause.patterns at index i
        Let param_name be parameters at index i

        Let pattern_check be build_pattern_match with pattern, param_name, ctx

        If pattern_check is not equal to 0:
            Add pattern_check to end of conditions
        End If
    End For

    Note: Add guard conditions
    For Each guard_seq in clause.guards:
        For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
            Let guard_hir be translate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
            Add guard_hir to end of conditions
        End For
    End For

    Note: Combine all conditions with AND
    If length of conditions is equal to 0:
        Return create_hir_bool with true
    End If

    If length of conditions is equal to 1:
        Return conditions at index 0
    End If

    Note: Build AND chain
    Let result be conditions at index 0
    For i from 1 to length of conditions minus 1:
        Set result to create_hir_binary_op with "and", result, conditions at index i
    End For

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Translates an Erlang pattern into a boolean expression that tests whether a
target variable matches. Returns null (which the caller interprets as
"trivially true") for variable patterns and the wildcard, because those
patterns always succeed - but variable patterns also have a SIDE EFFECT of
recording the binding in ctx.local_vars so subsequent body translations can
resolve the variable. Literal patterns become equality comparisons; list and
tuple patterns recursively check structure (is_list / is_tuple + size match)
before recursing into elements. Element access uses erlang:nth (lists) or
erlang:element (1-indexed tuples) to mirror the canonical Erlang accessors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "build_pattern_match" that takes pattern as ErlangExpression, target_var as String, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note: Build condition expression that checks if target_var matches pattern

    Note: Simple variable or wildcard - always matches
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Let var_name be pattern.expr_data at key "name"

        If var_name is equal to "_":
            Return null  Note: Wildcard always matches
        End If

        Note: Binding variable - record in context
        Let any_type be create_hir_type with "any" and a list containing nothing
        Set ctx.local_vars at key var_name to any_type

        Return null  Note: Variable pattern always matches
    End If

    Note: Atom literal - check equality
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_value be pattern.expr_data at key "value"
        Let target_expr be create_hir_var with target_var
        Let pattern_expr be create_hir_atom with atom_value
        Return create_hir_binary_op with "==", target_expr, pattern_expr
    End If

    Note: Integer literal - check equality
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "integer":
        Let int_value be pattern.expr_data at key "value"
        Set target_expr to create_hir_var with target_var
        Set pattern_expr to create_hir_int with int_value
        Return create_hir_binary_op with "==", target_expr, pattern_expr
    End If

    Note: List pattern - check structure and elements
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "list":
        Let elements be pattern.expr_data at key "elements"
        Let tail be pattern.expr_data at key "tail"

        Note: Build list structure check
        Let checks be a list containing nothing

        Note: Check if target is a list
        Set target_expr to create_hir_var with target_var
        Let is_list_check be create_hir_call with "erlang:is_list" and a list containing target_expr
        Add is_list_check to end of checks

        Note: Check list length (if no tail)
        If tail is equal to 0 and length of elements is greater than 0:
            Let length_call be create_hir_call with "erlang:length" and a list containing target_expr
            Let expected_len be create_hir_int with length of elements
            Let length_check be create_hir_binary_op with "==", length_call, expected_len
            Add length_check to end of checks
        End If

        Note: Check each element
        For i from 0 to length of elements minus 1:
            Let elem_pattern be elements at index i
            Let elem_temp be generate_temp_var with ctx

            Note: Extract element
            Let index_expr be create_hir_int with i
            Let elem_access be create_hir_call with "erlang:nth" and a list containing index_expr, target_expr

            Note: Build element match
            Let elem_check be build_pattern_match with elem_pattern, elem_temp, ctx

            If elem_check is not equal to 0:
                Add elem_check to end of checks
            End If
        End For

        Note: Combine all checks
        If length of checks is equal to 0:
            Return null
        End If

        Let result be checks at index 0
        For i from 1 to length of checks minus 1:
            Set result to create_hir_binary_op with "and", result, checks at index i
        End For

        Return result
    End If

    Note: Tuple pattern - check structure
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "tuple":
        Set elements to pattern.expr_data at key "elements"

        Set checks to a list containing nothing

        Note: Check if target is a tuple
        Set target_expr to create_hir_var with target_var
        Let is_tuple_check be create_hir_call with "erlang:is_tuple" and a list containing target_expr
        Add is_tuple_check to end of checks

        Note: Check tuple size
        Let size_call be create_hir_call with "erlang:tuple_size" and a list containing target_expr
        Let expected_size be create_hir_int with length of elements
        Let size_check be create_hir_binary_op with "==", size_call, expected_size
        Add size_check to end of checks

        Note: Check each element
        For i from 0 to length of elements minus 1:
            Set elem_pattern to elements at index i
            Set elem_temp to generate_temp_var with ctx

            Note: Extract element (1-indexed in Erlang)
            Set index_expr to create_hir_int with i plus 1
            Set elem_access to create_hir_call with "erlang:element" and a list containing index_expr, target_expr

            Note: Build element match
            Set elem_check to build_pattern_match with elem_pattern, elem_temp, ctx

            If elem_check is not equal to 0:
                Add elem_check to end of checks
            End If
        End For

        Note: Combine all checks
        Set result to checks at index 0
        For i from 1 to length of checks minus 1:
            Set result to create_hir_binary_op with "and", result, checks at index i
        End For

        Return result
    End If

    Note: Default - no additional check needed
    Return null
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Translates a sequence of expressions (e.g. the body of a function clause or
case arm) into a list of HIR statements. The last expression in the list
typically becomes the implicit return value; we do NOT wrap it in an
explicit return here because the surrounding HIR function form treats the
final statement's value as the return automatically. Sequence semantics are
left-to-right with no early termination.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_expressions" that takes exprs as List[ErlangExpression], ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns List[HIRStatement]:
    Let statements be a list containing nothing

    For i from 0 to length of exprs minus 1:
        Let expr be exprs at index i
        Let hir_expr be translate_expression with expr and ctx

        Note: Last expression is return value
        If i is equal to length of exprs minus 1:
            Let return_stmt be create_hir_return with hir_expr
            Add return_stmt to end of statements
        Otherwise:
            Note: Expression statement (side effect)
            Let expr_stmt be create_hir_expr_statement with hir_expr
            Add expr_stmt to end of statements
        End If
    End For

    Return statements
End Process

@Reasoning:
The central expression dispatcher routes on expr.expr_type string. Leaf
literals (atom, var, integer, float, string, char) are handled inline
because each maps to a single HIR helper; composite forms delegate to
specialised translators (translate_list, translate_tuple, translate_binary,
etc.). The fallthrough at the end records an error in ctx.errors and emits
a sentinel HIR error node so the rest of the module can still translate even
when one expression is unrecognised - this is essential for the
research/debugging workflow where partial Erlang support is acceptable.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_expression" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note: Translate Erlang expression to HIR expression

    Note: Atom literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_value be expr.expr_data at key "value"
        Return create_hir_atom with atom_value
    End If

    Note: Variable reference
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Let var_name be expr.expr_data at key "name"
        Return create_hir_var with var_name
    End If

    Note: Integer literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "integer":
        Let int_value be expr.expr_data at key "value"
        Return create_hir_int with int_value
    End If

    Note: Float literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "float":
        Let float_value be expr.expr_data at key "value"
        Return create_hir_float with float_value
    End If

    Note: String literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "string":
        Let str_value be expr.expr_data at key "value"
        Return create_hir_string with str_value
    End If

    Note: Character literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "char":
        Let char_value be expr.expr_data at key "value"
        Return create_hir_char with char_value
    End If

    Note: List literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "list":
        Return translate_list with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Tuple literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "tuple":
        Return translate_tuple with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Binary literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "binary":
        Return translate_binary with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Binary operator
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "op":
        Return translate_binary_op with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Unary operator
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "unary_op":
        Return translate_unary_op with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Function call
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "call":
        Return translate_call with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Fun expression (anonymous function)
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "fun":
        Return translate_fun with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Case expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "case":
        Return translate_case with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: If expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "if":
        Return translate_if with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Receive expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "receive":
        Return translate_receive with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Try expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "try":
        Return translate_try with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Begin expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "begin":
        Return translate_begin with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: List comprehension
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "list_comprehension":
        Return translate_list_comprehension with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Binary comprehension
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "binary_comprehension":
        Return translate_binary_comprehension with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Record creation
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "record_create":
        Return translate_record_create with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Record access
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "record_access":
        Return translate_record_access with expr and ctx
    End If

    Note: Macro reference
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "macro":
        Let macro_name be expr.expr_data at key "name"
        Return create_hir_macro with macro_name
    End If

    Note: Default - unsupported expression
    Add "Unsupported Erlang expression type: " joined with expr.expr_type to end of ctx.errors
    Return create_hir_error with "unsupported_expression"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang lists come in two shapes: proper lists [e1, e2, e3] and improper lists
[H | T] where T is itself a list (or anything; Erlang permits improper
lists). Proper lists become a single HIR list literal. Improper lists are
built right-to-left as a chain of erlang:cons calls so the tail expression
appears at the rightmost position and each head prepends one element at a
time. This matches how Erlang's VM constructs lists internally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_list" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let elements be expr.expr_data at key "elements"
    Let tail be expr.expr_data at key "tail"

    Let hir_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let hir_elem be translate_expression with elem and ctx
        Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
    End For

    Note: Proper list (no tail)
    If tail is equal to 0:
        Return create_hir_list with hir_elements
    End If

    Note: Improper list with tail [H|T]
    Note: Build list cons operations
    Let result be translate_expression with tail and ctx

    Note: Build list from right to left
    Let i be length of hir_elements minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let elem be hir_elements at index i
        Set result to create_hir_call with "erlang:cons" and a list containing elem, result
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuples are fixed-arity heterogeneous containers and translate directly to
an HIR tuple value. Element order matters and is preserved verbatim. Tuple
literals are first-class HIR primitives because too many downstream targets
have native tuple types for it to be worth lowering to a list-based form
here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_tuple" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let elements be expr.expr_data at key "elements"

    Let hir_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let hir_elem be translate_expression with elem and ctx
        Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
    End For

    Return create_hir_tuple with hir_elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang binary syntax '<<S1, S2, ...>>' constructs a binary from a sequence
of segments, each carrying a value expression, an optional size, and a list
of type specifiers (integer/float/binary/utf8/etc., big/little endian,
signed/unsigned). We translate each segment into a dictionary preserving all
three components so backends can reproduce the bit-level layout exactly.
Specifiers are forwarded verbatim because Erlang's binary spec semantics are
intricate and the backend is in the best position to lower them.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let segments be expr.expr_data at key "segments"

    Note: Translate binary to HIR binary construction
    Let hir_segments be a list containing nothing

    For Each segment in segments:
        Let value be translate_expression with segment at key "value" and ctx
        Let size be segment at key "size"
        Let specifiers be segment at key "specifiers"

        Let hir_size be null
        If size is not equal to 0:
            Set hir_size to translate_expression with size and ctx
        End If

        Let segment_info be a dictionary containing:
            "value" as value,
            "size" as hir_size,
            "specifiers" as specifiers
        End Dictionary

        Add segment_info to end of hir_segments
    End For

    Return create_hir_binary with hir_segments
End Process

@Reasoning:
Most Erlang binary operators map directly to HIR operator strings. Exceptions
require special HIR forms: '!' is the message-send operator (create_hir_send),
'=' is pattern match (create_hir_match), '++' and '--' are list operations
implemented as erlang:append / erlang:subtract calls because HIR has no
dedicated nodes for them. Other special spellings (=:=, =/=, andalso, orelse,
div, rem, b* bitwise) are rewritten to HIR's operator spelling without
semantic change. The default branch sets hir_op = operator so unrecognised
operators pass through (useful when Erlang adds new operator spellings the
translator hasn't been updated for).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary_op" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let operator be expr.expr_data at key "operator"
    Let left be translate_expression with expr.expr_data at key "left" and ctx
    Let right be translate_expression with expr.expr_data at key "right" and ctx

    Note: Map Erlang operators to HIR operators
    Let hir_op be operator

    Note: Special Erlang operators
    If operator is equal to "!":
        Note: Message send operator
        Return create_hir_send with left and right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "=":
        Note: Pattern match operator
        Return create_hir_match with left and right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "++":
        Note: List concatenation
        Return create_hir_call with "erlang:append" and a list containing left, right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "--":
        Note: List subtraction
        Return create_hir_call with "erlang:subtract" and a list containing left, right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "=:=":
        Set hir_op to "==="  Note: Exact equality

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "=/=":
        Set hir_op to "!=="  Note: Exact inequality

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "andalso":
        Set hir_op to "and"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "orelse":
        Set hir_op to "or"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "div":
        Set hir_op to "/"  Note: Integer division

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "rem":
        Set hir_op to "%"  Note: Remainder

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "band":
        Set hir_op to "&"  Note: Bitwise AND

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bor":
        Set hir_op to "|"  Note: Bitwise OR

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bxor":
        Set hir_op to "^"  Note: Bitwise XOR

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bsl":
        Set hir_op to "<<"  Note: Bit shift left

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bsr":
        Set hir_op to ">>"  Note: Bit shift right
    End If

    Return create_hir_binary_op with hir_op, left, right
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's three unary operators are +, -, not, and bnot. '+' and '-' pass
through unchanged. 'not' becomes '!' to match HIR's boolean negation
spelling, and 'bnot' becomes '~' for bitwise negation. The operator string
substitution is the entirety of the transformation; HIR's unary node form is
otherwise identical.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_unary_op" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let operator be expr.expr_data at key "operator"
    Let operand be translate_expression with expr.expr_data at key "operand" and ctx

    Note: Map Erlang unary operators to HIR
    Let hir_op be operator

    If operator is equal to "not":
        Set hir_op to "!"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bnot":
        Set hir_op to "~"  Note: Bitwise NOT
    End If

    Return create_hir_unary_op with hir_op and operand
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang calls come in three flavours: local 'foo(args)', remote
'mod:foo(args)' (an explicit ':' operator at the AST level), and higher-order
'F(args)' where F is a function-valued expression. We disambiguate by the
shape of the function position: a ':' op means remote, an atom literal means
local, anything else means higher-order. Local calls are always qualified
with ctx.current_module so HIR consumers see fully-qualified names
everywhere - this matches Erlang's actual runtime behaviour where the VM
resolves bare function names against the calling module.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_call" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let function be expr.expr_data at key "function"
    Let arguments be expr.expr_data at key "arguments"

    Note: Translate arguments
    Let hir_args be a list containing nothing
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Let hir_arg be translate_expression with arg and ctx
        Add hir_arg to end of hir_args
    End For

    Note: Check if remote call (Module:Function)
    If function.expr_type is equal to "op" and function.expr_data at key "operator" is equal to ":":
        Let module_expr be function.expr_data at key "left"
        Let func_expr be function.expr_data at key "right"

        Let module_name be ""
        Let func_name be ""

        If module_expr.expr_type is equal to "atom":
            Set module_name to module_expr.expr_data at key "value"
        End If

        If func_expr.expr_type is equal to "atom":
            Set func_name to func_expr.expr_data at key "value"
        End If

        Let qualified_name be module_name joined with ":" joined with func_name

        Return create_hir_call with qualified_name and hir_args
    End If

    Note: Local call
    If function.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Set func_name to function.expr_data at key "value"

        Note: Qualify with current module
        Set qualified_name to ctx.current_module joined with ":" joined with func_name

        Return create_hir_call with qualified_name and hir_args
    End If

    Note: Higher-order call (function variable)
    Set func_expr to translate_expression with function and ctx
    Return create_hir_call_indirect with func_expr and hir_args
End Process

@Reasoning:
'fun' expressions have three syntactic forms: a remote reference
'fun M:F/N' becomes a HIR function reference with qualified name and arity;
a local reference 'fun F/N' is qualified with current_module before becoming
a function reference; an anonymous 'fun(args)->body end' (possibly with
multiple clauses) becomes a lambda. The anonymous case re-uses
translate_clauses_with_dispatch for the body so the clause-dispatch logic is
shared between named functions and anonymous lambdas.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_fun" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let fun_type be expr.expr_data at key "type"

    Note: Function reference: fun Module:Function/Arity or fun Function/Arity
    If fun_type is equal to "remote_ref":
        Let module_name be expr.expr_data at key "module"
        Let func_name be expr.expr_data at key "function"
        Let arity be expr.expr_data at key "arity"

        Let qualified_name be module_name joined with ":" joined with func_name

        Return create_hir_function_ref with qualified_name and arity

    Otherwise If fun_type is equal to "local_ref":
        Set func_name to expr.expr_data at key "function"
        Set arity to expr.expr_data at key "arity"

        Set qualified_name to ctx.current_module joined with ":" joined with func_name

        Return create_hir_function_ref with qualified_name and arity
    End If

    Note: Anonymous function with clauses
    If fun_type is equal to "anonymous":
        Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"

        Note: Build lambda from clauses
        Note: Use first clause to determine arity
        Let first_clause be clauses at index 0
        Set arity to length of first_clause.patterns

        Note: Create parameter list
        Let parameters be a list containing nothing
        For i from 0 to arity minus 1:
            Let param_name be "arg" joined with string representation of i
            Add param_name to end of parameters
        End For

        Note: Build lambda body with clause dispatch
        Let lambda_body be translate_clauses_with_dispatch with clauses, parameters, ctx

        Note: Create parameter types
        Let param_types be a list containing nothing
        For i from 0 to arity minus 1:
            Let any_type be create_hir_type with "any" and a list containing nothing
            Add any_type to end of param_types
        End For

        Let return_type be create_hir_type with "any" and a list containing nothing

        Return create_hir_lambda with parameters, param_types, return_type, lambda_body
    End If

    Note: Default
    Return create_hir_error with "unsupported_fun_type"
End Process

@Reasoning:
'case Expr of Patterns... end' tests Expr against each clause's pattern,
running the body of the first matching clause. We translate to a HIR match
expression with a list of (pattern, guard, body) branches. Each branch
preserves the pattern as a translated HIR pattern (so the match expression
can perform real structural matching, not just equality testing), the guard
sequence (combined into a single boolean via AND), and the translated body
statements. The branches list keeps source order so the first-match
semantics persist into HIR consumers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_case" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let scrutinee be translate_expression with expr.expr_data at key "scrutinee" and ctx
    Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"

    Note: Build match expression with branches
    Let branches be a list containing nothing

    For Each clause in clauses:
        Note: Each clause has pattern, guards, and body
        Let pattern be clause.patterns at index 0
        Let guards be clause.guards
        Let body be clause.body

        Note: Translate pattern to HIR pattern
        Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern and ctx

        Note: Translate guards to conditions
        Let hir_guards be a list containing nothing
        For Each guard_seq in guards:
            For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
            End For
        End For

        Note: Translate body
        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body and ctx

        Let branch_info be a dictionary containing:
            "pattern" as hir_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add branch_info to end of branches
    End For

    Return create_hir_match_expr with scrutinee and branches
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's 'if' is not a binary if/else - it is a sequence of guard-protected
clauses where the first clause whose guards all succeed wins. We translate
to nested HIR if expressions: each clause's guards combine via AND to form a
condition, and the bodies become the then-branches. If no clause matches the
runtime raises if_clause; we do not emit that fallthrough error here because
the if-chain naturally terminates at the last clause's else (or null).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_if" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"

    Note: Build nested if-else from guard sequences
    Let if_expr be null

    For i from 0 to length of clauses minus 1:
        Let clause be clauses at index i

        Note: Translate guards to condition
        Let condition be null
        If length of clause.guards is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be clause.guards at index 0
            Let guard_conditions be a list containing nothing

            For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of guard_conditions
            End For

            Note: Combine with AND
            If length of guard_conditions is greater than 0:
                Set condition to guard_conditions at index 0
                For j from 1 to length of guard_conditions minus 1:
                    Set condition to create_hir_binary_op with "and", condition, guard_conditions at index j
                End For
            End If
        End If

        Note: Translate body
        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with clause.body and ctx

        Note: Build if expression
        If i is equal to 0:
            Set if_expr to create_hir_if_expr with condition, hir_body, a list containing nothing
        Otherwise:
            Note: Add to else chain
            Note: Build proper else-if chain for multiple case clauses
            Let clause_count be proc list_length from List with clauses
            If clause_count is greater than 1:
                Let case_chain be proc build_case_chain with ctx, clauses, hir_case
                Return case_chain
            End If
            Set if_expr to create_hir_if_expr with condition, hir_body, a list containing nothing
        End If
    End For

    Return if_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
'receive ... after T -> ... end' is Erlang's mailbox primitive: the calling
process blocks reading from its mailbox until a message matches one of the
clauses or the timeout T fires. We translate clauses identically to
case-clauses (each becomes a {pattern, guards, body} dictionary), plus an
optional timeout expression and after-body. The HIR receive node is a
first-class construct because no other target language has identical
semantics; backends lower it differently depending on whether they target
actor-model runtimes, channel-based concurrency, or pure thread+queue.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_receive" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"
    Let after_timeout be expr.expr_data at key "after_timeout"
    Let after_body be expr.expr_data at key "after_body"

    Note: Build receive expression
    Let receive_clauses be a list containing nothing

    For Each clause in clauses:
        Let pattern be clause.patterns at index 0
        Let guards be clause.guards
        Let body be clause.body

        Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern and ctx

        Let hir_guards be a list containing nothing
        For Each guard_seq in guards:
            For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
            End For
        End For

        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body and ctx

        Let clause_info be a dictionary containing:
            "pattern" as hir_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add clause_info to end of receive_clauses
    End For

    Note: Translate timeout
    Let hir_timeout be null
    If after_timeout is not equal to 0:
        Set hir_timeout to translate_expression with after_timeout and ctx
    End If

    Let hir_after_body be a list containing nothing
    If length of after_body is greater than 0:
        Set hir_after_body to translate_expressions with after_body and ctx
    End If

    Return create_hir_receive with receive_clauses, hir_timeout, hir_after_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
'try Body of Patterns... catch Clauses... after AfterBody end' is Erlang's
unified exception construct. We preserve all four sections: the try body,
the optional 'of' clauses that pattern-match the try body's value (when
present, the try succeeds only when an of clause matches), the catch
clauses keyed by exception class (error/exit/throw), and the after body
that always runs for cleanup. Catch clauses carry both a class and a
pattern, which the backend uses to filter exceptions by kind and then
match the exception term itself.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_try" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let try_body be expr.expr_data at key "try_body"
    Let of_clauses be expr.expr_data at key "of_clauses"
    Let catch_clauses be expr.expr_data at key "catch_clauses"
    Let after_body be expr.expr_data at key "after_body"

    Note: Translate try body
    Let hir_try_body be translate_expressions with try_body and ctx

    Note: Translate of clauses
    Let hir_of_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each clause in of_clauses:
        Let pattern be clause.patterns at index 0
        Let guards be clause.guards
        Let body be clause.body

        Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern and ctx

        Let hir_guards be a list containing nothing
        For Each guard_seq in guards:
            For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
            End For
        End For

        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body and ctx

        Let clause_info be a dictionary containing:
            "pattern" as hir_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add clause_info to end of hir_of_clauses
    End For

    Note: Translate catch clauses
    Let hir_catch_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each catch_data in catch_clauses:
        Let exception_class be catch_data at key "exception_class"
        Let exception_pattern be catch_data at key "exception_pattern"
        Set guards to catch_data at key "guards"
        Set body to catch_data at key "body"

        Let hir_exception_class be null
        If exception_class is not equal to 0:
            Set hir_exception_class to translate_expression with exception_class and ctx
        End If

        Let hir_exception_pattern be translate_pattern with exception_pattern and ctx

        Set hir_guards to a list containing nothing
        For Each guard_expr in guards:
            Set hir_guard to translate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
            Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
        End For

        Set hir_body to translate_expressions with body and ctx

        Let catch_info be a dictionary containing:
            "exception_class" as hir_exception_class,
            "exception_pattern" as hir_exception_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add catch_info to end of hir_catch_clauses
    End For

    Note: Translate after body
    Let hir_after_body be a list containing nothing
    If length of after_body is greater than 0:
        Set hir_after_body to translate_expressions with after_body and ctx
    End If

    Return create_hir_try with hir_try_body, hir_of_clauses, hir_catch_clauses, hir_after_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
'begin ... end' is Erlang's block expression that groups a sequence of
expressions into one expression whose value is the last sub-expression. We
translate the body via translate_expressions (which handles the
last-expression-is-return convention) and wrap in a HIR block. No special
scope semantics apply because Erlang's begin-end does not introduce a new
binding scope - bindings inside the block escape into the surrounding
scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_begin" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let body be expr.expr_data at key "body"
    Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body and ctx

    Note: Begin-end is just a block expression
    Return create_hir_block with hir_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
List comprehensions '[Template || Q1, Q2, ...]' carry one template expression
and a list of qualifiers, each either a generator (Pat <- List) or a filter
(BoolExpr). We translate the template once and each qualifier into a typed
dictionary preserving its kind. Multiple qualifiers are handled either by
the dedicated build_nested_comprehension_loops helper (when there are
several, allowing proper nesting) or inline (single qualifier). The HIR
comprehension node keeps the generator/filter distinction so backends can
either lower to nested loops or use a target language's own comprehension.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_list_comprehension" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let template be expr.expr_data at key "template"
    Let qualifiers be expr.expr_data at key "qualifiers"

    Note: Build nested loops and filters for comprehension
    Note: [Template || Qualifier1, Qualifier2, ...]

    Note: Translate template
    Let hir_template be translate_expression with template and ctx

    Note: Build comprehension structure
    Note: Build nested loops for multiple qualifiers in comprehension
    Let qualifier_count be proc list_length from List with qualifiers
    If qualifier_count is greater than 1:
        Let nested_loops be proc build_nested_comprehension_loops with ctx, hir_template, qualifiers
        Return nested_loops
    End If
    Let hir_qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    For Each qualifier in qualifiers:
        Let qual_type be qualifier at key "type"

        If qual_type is equal to "generator":
            Let pattern be qualifier at key "pattern"
            Let list_expr be qualifier at key "list"

            Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern and ctx
            Let hir_list be translate_expression with list_expr and ctx

            Let gen_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "generator",
                "pattern" as hir_pattern,
                "list" as hir_list
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_info to end of hir_qualifiers

        Otherwise If qual_type is equal to "filter":
            Let filter_expr be qualifier at key "expression"
            Let hir_filter be translate_expression with filter_expr and ctx

            Let filter_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as hir_filter
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_info to end of hir_qualifiers
        End If
    End For

    Return create_hir_list_comprehension with hir_template and hir_qualifiers
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary comprehensions '<< Template || Q1, Q2, ... >>' are the binary-data
counterpart to list comprehensions, producing a binary instead of a list.
The template is a binary segment dictionary rather than an arbitrary
expression. Qualifiers can be ordinary list generators ('Pat <- List') OR
binary generators ('Pat <= Binary'); we distinguish via qual_type and route
the source through either "list" or "binary" key so the backend knows which
collection kind to iterate.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary_comprehension" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let template be expr.expr_data at key "template"
    Let qualifiers be expr.expr_data at key "qualifiers"

    Note: Similar to list comprehension but produces binary
    Let hir_template be template  Note: Template is segment dict

    Let hir_qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    For Each qualifier in qualifiers:
        Let qual_type be qualifier at key "type"

        If qual_type is equal to "generator" or qual_type is equal to "binary_generator":
            Let pattern be qualifier at key "pattern"
            Let source_key be "list"
            If qual_type is equal to "binary_generator":
                Set source_key to "binary"
            End If
            Let source_expr be qualifier at key source_key

            Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern and ctx
            Let hir_source be translate_expression with source_expr and ctx

            Let gen_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as qual_type,
                "pattern" as hir_pattern,
                "source" as hir_source
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_info to end of hir_qualifiers

        Otherwise If qual_type is equal to "filter":
            Let filter_expr be qualifier at key "expression"
            Let hir_filter be translate_expression with filter_expr and ctx

            Let filter_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as hir_filter
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_info to end of hir_qualifiers
        End If
    End For

    Return create_hir_binary_comprehension with hir_template and hir_qualifiers
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang records are tuples with named field access; we translate them to HIR
record constructions that preserve the record name (for type resolution),
the field/value map, and an optional base record (Erlang's '#Record{X=Y}'
update form). The field map omits fields not explicitly given - they will
take default values from the record definition at the time the HIR is
lowered. The record_def lookup in ctx.records is currently used only for
later type checking; field validation happens during semantic analysis.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_record_create" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let record_name be expr.expr_data at key "name"
    Let fields be expr.expr_data at key "fields"
    Let base be expr.expr_data at key "base"

    Note: Get record definition from context
    Let record_def be ctx.records at key record_name

    Note: Build field map
    Let hir_fields be a dictionary containing nothing

    For Each field_data in fields:
        Let field_name be field_data at key "name"
        Let field_value be field_data at key "value"

        Let hir_value be translate_expression with field_value and ctx
        Set hir_fields at key field_name to hir_value
    End For

    Note: Handle record update
    Let hir_base be null
    If base is not equal to 0:
        Set hir_base to translate_expression with base and ctx
    End If

    Return create_hir_record with record_name, hir_fields, hir_base
End Process

@Reasoning:
'Record#name.field' is Erlang's record field access syntax. We translate the
record expression and pair it with the field name (kept as a string because
record field-to-tuple-index resolution happens during semantic analysis when
the record definition is available). HIR consumers handling record_access
nodes are expected to consult the record definition catalogue separately.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_record_access" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let record be expr.expr_data at key "record"
    Let field be expr.expr_data at key "field"

    Let hir_record be translate_expression with record and ctx

    Return create_hir_record_access with hir_record and field
End Process

@Reasoning:
This is the pattern-to-HIR-pattern translator, used by case/receive/try
clauses where the HIR consumer can match patterns structurally rather than
emitting equality tests. It mirrors build_pattern_match (which emits boolean
conditions) but produces actual HIR pattern objects: variables become
var_patterns, literals become literal_patterns, lists become list_patterns
with an optional tail pattern, tuples become tuple_patterns, and the special
"_" wildcard becomes a wildcard_pattern. Unrecognised pattern shapes return
a wildcard so HIR consumers default to "match anything", which keeps
translation partial-safe at the cost of potentially admitting matches the
original Erlang would have rejected.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_pattern" that takes pattern as ErlangExpression and ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Note: Translate Erlang pattern to HIR pattern

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Let var_name be pattern.expr_data at key "name"
        Return create_hir_var_pattern with var_name
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_value be pattern.expr_data at key "value"
        Return create_hir_literal_pattern with atom_value
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "integer":
        Let int_value be pattern.expr_data at key "value"
        Return create_hir_literal_pattern with int_value
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "list":
        Let elements be pattern.expr_data at key "elements"
        Let tail be pattern.expr_data at key "tail"

        Let hir_elements be a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Let hir_elem be translate_pattern with elem and ctx
            Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
        End For

        Let hir_tail be null
        If tail is not equal to 0:
            Set hir_tail to translate_pattern with tail and ctx
        End If

        Return create_hir_list_pattern with hir_elements and hir_tail
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "tuple":
        Set elements to pattern.expr_data at key "elements"

        Set hir_elements to a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Set hir_elem to translate_pattern with elem and ctx
            Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
        End For

        Return create_hir_tuple_pattern with hir_elements
    End If

    Note: Default - variable pattern
    Return create_hir_wildcard_pattern
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR CREATION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor for HIRType records used wherever the translator needs to embed
a concrete type reference (parameter types, return types, generic
instantiations). The two-field structure (name + type-argument list) is the
minimal representation that supports both monomorphic types like "integer"
and parametric forms like Dict[String, Atom].
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_type" that takes type_name as String, type_args as List[Any] returns HIRType:
    Return a value of type HIRType with
        name as type_name,
        args as type_args
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wraps an atom literal as an HIRExpression. Atoms are distinguished from
other string-valued literals by their kind tag so downstream consumers
(particularly target-language renderers) emit the correct syntactic form -
e.g. ':symbol' in Ruby, ":atom" in Elixir, "Symbol(:foo)" in Racket.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_atom" that takes value as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "atom",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variable reference constructor. The data field carries the source identifier
verbatim; binding resolution is the responsibility of the consumer once the
HIR is paired with a scope analysis pass.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_var" that takes name as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "var",
        data as name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Integer literal constructor. The Integer type is used directly because
Erlang integers are arbitrary-precision in semantics but typically fit into
machine-word sizes for the translator's purposes; downstream type analysis
may widen the representation later when overflow is provable.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_int" that takes value as Integer returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "int",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Float literal constructor. Erlang floats are 64-bit IEEE doubles; we accept
a Float here and emit a HIR float node with the value preserved bit-exactly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_float" that takes value as Float returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "float",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
String literal constructor. Note that Erlang "strings" are actually lists of
integers (Unicode code points) at the language level, but we expose them as
HIR string nodes so the backend can emit native string types where the
target language has them; targets that need to preserve Erlang's
list-of-integers semantics can re-lower at code emission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_string" that takes value as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "string",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Character literal constructor. Erlang's '$X' notation yields the integer
code point of X; we keep the original character form here as a String for
display fidelity, with backends free to lower to integer if their target
language treats characters as integers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_char" that takes value as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "char",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean literal constructor. Erlang booleans are the atoms 'true' and
'false' at the runtime level; we expose them as a distinct HIR kind so
backends with native booleans can emit those directly rather than going
through the atom path.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_bool" that takes value as Boolean returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "bool",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Proper-list constructor (no tail). For improper lists 'translate_list'
synthesises a chain of erlang:cons calls via create_hir_call rather than
calling this constructor, so a 'list' HIR node always represents a fully-
materialised proper list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "list",
        data as elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuple constructor for fixed-arity heterogeneous tuples. Distinct from list
so backends can map to native tuple/record types where available; in
languages without tuples the backend lowers to a struct or array.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_tuple" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "tuple",
        data as elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary literal constructor for Erlang's '<<...>>' bit-syntax. The segments
list preserves each segment's value/size/specifiers as a dictionary so the
backend can reproduce the precise bit-level layout.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_binary" that takes segments as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "binary",
        data as segments
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary-operator constructor. The op field carries the post-translation
operator string (after translate_binary_op has normalised Erlang-specific
spellings to HIR spellings), and left/right are the operand HIR
expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_binary_op" that takes operator as String, left as HIRExpression, right as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let op_data be a dictionary containing:
        "op" as operator,
        "left" as left,
        "right" as right
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "binary_op",
        data as op_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary-operator constructor mirroring create_hir_binary_op but with a single
operand. The op spelling is the post-normalisation HIR form ('!', '~', '-',
'+'), set by translate_unary_op before this constructor is invoked.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_unary_op" that takes operator as String, operand as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let op_data be a dictionary containing:
        "op" as operator,
        "operand" as operand
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "unary_op",
        data as op_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Static call constructor for calls whose target is a fully-qualified
'Module:function' or 'self_module:function' string. The function_name is
pre-qualified by translate_call so consumers do not need to re-resolve
module context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_call" that takes function_name as String, arguments as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Let call_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function_name,
        "args" as arguments
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "call",
        data as call_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indirect call constructor for higher-order calls where the callee is itself
an expression (a function variable, a lambda, the result of another call).
Distinguished from create_hir_call by the kind tag so backends can choose
between direct dispatch and value-level call mechanism.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_call_indirect" that takes function as HIRExpression, arguments as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Let call_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function,
        "args" as arguments
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "call_indirect",
        data as call_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Anonymous-function (lambda) constructor. Preserves parameter names, their
types, the return type, and the body statement list. Used both for explicit
'fun(args) -> body end' source and for synthetic lambdas produced when
translating multi-clause anonymous functions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_lambda" that takes parameters as List[String], param_types as List[HIRType], return_type as HIRType, body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let lambda_data be a dictionary containing:
        "parameters" as parameters,
        "param_types" as param_types,
        "return_type" as return_type,
        "body" as body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "lambda",
        data as lambda_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function reference constructor for the 'fun M:F/N' and 'fun F/N' Erlang
forms. Carries name and arity rather than a callable value so the backend
can decide whether to emit a closure object, a function pointer, or a
delegate depending on its target language idiom.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_function_ref" that takes function_name as String, arity as Integer returns HIRExpression:
    Let ref_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function_name,
        "arity" as arity
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "function_ref",
        data as ref_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Message-send constructor for the Erlang '!' operator. Distinct from a
regular call because the runtime semantics involve enqueueing into a
process mailbox rather than synchronous invocation; backends targeting
actor frameworks lower this to their framework's send primitive.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_send" that takes destination as HIRExpression, message as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let send_data be a dictionary containing:
        "destination" as destination,
        "message" as message
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "send",
        data as send_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's '=' match operator constructor. Distinct from assignment because
the LHS is a pattern (which may destructure) and the operator can fail at
runtime if the pattern does not match the value. Backends translating to
languages without pattern-match-as-expression lower to a conditional and
an exception throw on mismatch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_match" that takes pattern as HIRExpression, value as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let match_data be a dictionary containing:
        "pattern" as pattern,
        "value" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "match",
        data as match_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Case-expression constructor: holds the scrutinee and a list of
{pattern, guards, body} branches. The branches list is in source order to
preserve first-match semantics. Used by translate_case for Erlang's 'case
... of ... end' construct.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_match_expr" that takes scrutinee as HIRExpression, branches as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Let match_data be a dictionary containing:
        "scrutinee" as scrutinee,
        "branches" as branches
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "match_expr",
        data as match_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
If-expression constructor with explicit then/else statement lists. Used by
translate_if to build the nested chain for Erlang's 'if ... end'. The else
list is empty when the source had no terminating else clause, in which case
the runtime would raise if_clause if no preceding clause matched.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_if_expr" that takes condition as HIRExpression, then_body as List[HIRStatement], else_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let if_data be a dictionary containing:
        "condition" as condition,
        "then" as then_body,
        "else" as else_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "if_expr",
        data as if_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Receive-expression constructor for Erlang's mailbox primitive. Holds the
list of receive clauses (each with pattern+guards+body), an optional
timeout expression, and the after-body statements that run if the timeout
fires. Both timeout and after_body may be null when no 'after' clause was
present.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_receive" that takes clauses as List[Any], timeout as HIRExpression, after_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let receive_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses,
        "timeout" as timeout,
        "after" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "receive",
        data as receive_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Try-expression constructor preserving all four sections of Erlang's
try/of/catch/after: the protected body, the 'of' value-match clauses (empty
when absent), the catch clauses keyed by exception class, and the always-
runs after-body. Backends with simpler exception models flatten the of and
catch sections during lowering.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_try" that takes try_body as List[HIRStatement], of_clauses as List[Any], catch_clauses as List[Any], after_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let try_data be a dictionary containing:
        "try" as try_body,
        "of" as of_clauses,
        "catch" as catch_clauses,
        "after" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "try",
        data as try_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Block expression constructor wrapping a statement list. Used for 'begin
... end' and for synthetic blocks produced when an expression context needs
multiple statements. The block value is the value of its last sub-statement.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_block" that takes body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "block",
        data as body
End Process

@Reasoning:
List comprehension constructor preserving template and qualifier list.
Distinct from the binary comprehension constructor only by its kind tag and
the type of the template (full expression here vs. binary-segment dict for
binary comprehensions).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list_comprehension" that takes template as HIRExpression, qualifiers as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Let comp_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "list_comprehension",
        data as comp_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary comprehension constructor; the template is typed Any because it is
a segment dictionary rather than an HIRExpression. Backends recognise the
kind tag and treat the template as bit-syntax rather than ordinary
expression syntax.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_binary_comprehension" that takes template as Any, qualifiers as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Let comp_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "binary_comprehension",
        data as comp_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Record-creation constructor for '#name{field=value, ...}' and the update
form '#name{Base|...}'. Base is null for fresh-record creation and non-null
for update; the field map carries only EXPLICITLY-SET fields (omitted
fields default at lower-level lowering).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_record" that takes name as String, fields as Dictionary[String, HIRExpression], base as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let record_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as name,
        "fields" as fields,
        "base" as base
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "record",
        data as record_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Record-access constructor for 'Record#name.field'. The field is held as a
string because resolving it to a tuple slot index requires the record
definition, which is consulted during semantic analysis.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_record_access" that takes record as HIRExpression, field as String returns HIRExpression:
    Let access_data be a dictionary containing:
        "record" as record,
        "field" as field
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "record_access",
        data as access_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Macro reference constructor for '?MACRO_NAME'. The translator does not
expand the macro - it preserves the reference so a separate pre-processing
or expansion pass can substitute the macro body when the macro definitions
table is available.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_macro" that takes name as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "macro",
        data as name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Error sentinel expression used when the translator encounters an unsupported
construct. The kind tag "error" lets HIR consumers either propagate the
error to the user or substitute a runtime exception throw, depending on
their error-handling policy.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_error" that takes message as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "error",
        data as message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Return-statement constructor. Used in translate_expressions to mark the
last expression in a sequence as the value to return from the enclosing
function/clause.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_return" that takes value as HIRExpression returns HIRStatement:
    Return a value of type HIRStatement with
        stmt_type as "return",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Expression-statement constructor. Wraps an expression as a statement so it
appears in a statement-list context where its value is discarded. Required
because HIR statement lists do not accept bare expression values.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_expr_statement" that takes expr as HIRExpression returns HIRStatement:
    Return a value of type HIRStatement with
        stmt_type as "expr",
        data as expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Statement-position if constructor (companion to create_hir_if_expr which
produces an if EXPRESSION). Used for clause dispatch in
translate_clauses_with_dispatch where the if must be a top-level statement
rather than a sub-expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_if" that takes condition as HIRExpression, then_body as List[HIRStatement], else_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRStatement:
    Let if_data be a dictionary containing:
        "condition" as condition,
        "then" as then_body,
        "else" as else_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRStatement with
        stmt_type as "if",
        data as if_data
End Process

Note: Pattern creation helpers

@Reasoning:
Variable-binding pattern constructor. Used by translate_pattern when an
Erlang variable appears in pattern position; the binding semantics (capture
the matched value into the named slot) is the HIR consumer's job.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_var_pattern" that takes name as String returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "var",
        data as name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Literal pattern constructor for atoms, integers, floats, strings, and
chars in pattern position. Match semantics are exact-equality.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_literal_pattern" that takes value as Any returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "literal",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
List-shape pattern constructor with optional cons-tail. The tail captures
the '[H|T]' / '[A,B|T]' forms; for proper-list patterns tail is null.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list_pattern" that takes elements as List[ErlangPatternIR], tail as ErlangPatternIR returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Let list_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as elements,
        "tail" as tail
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "list",
        data as list_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuple-shape pattern constructor for '{A,B,C}' patterns. Arity matching is
implied by element list length and is the HIR consumer's responsibility to
verify against the scrutinee.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_tuple_pattern" that takes elements as List[ErlangPatternIR] returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "tuple",
        data as elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wildcard pattern constructor. Always matches and binds nothing. Carries
the string "_" as data for source-reconstruction fidelity even though the
match semantics depend only on the pattern_type tag.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_wildcard_pattern" returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "wildcard",
        data as "_"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TRANSLATION ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point with the canonical translator name. Delegates to the
fully-named translate_erlang_module_to_hir which does the actual work; this
indirection exists so external callers see a name that matches the module
file convention without losing the more-descriptive internal function name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_erlang_to_hir" that takes erl_module as ErlangModule returns HIRModule:
    Return translate_erlang_module_to_hir with erl_module
End Process
